holds the national picture collection

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:05.860
of the United States.

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:09.200
While international in scope, the
collections are particularly rich

00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:14.480 position:69%
in materials either produced in the US or
documenting the history of lives, interests,

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:17.450 position:63%
and achievements of the American people.

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:22.170 position:59%
The 15.6 million collection, images
in the collection include photographs,

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:26.750
by far the most common format, fine
and popular prints and drawings,

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:30.080
posters and architectural
and engineering drawings.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:34.700 position:63%
Every year on average, the
collections grow by about 300,000 items,

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:39.210
and we digitize about 50,000 images
to add to our online catalog.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:44.810 position:73%
More than 1.2 million images are available
online through the Library of Congress website,

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:48.890
and we'll start by talking about
how you can find those images.

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:53.090 position:70%
Be aware that guidance and help with our
questions is available on site at the Library

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.620 position:64%
of Congress in the Prints and
Photographs Reading Room and from offsite

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:58.800 position:56%
through the Ask a Librarian service.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:03.390 position:59%
On the Library of Congress website,
there are many places to find visuals.

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:07.880 position:67%
We will include a few slides at the end of
our presentation today to help you find all

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:11.800
of the online sources for images
through the Library of Congress.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.410 position:73%
While the bulk of the images at the Library are
found in the Prints and Photographs Division,

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:20.310 position:58%
with the Library of Congress search
system, you can find visual materials

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:23.810
from throughout the Library's
divisions on our website.

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:30.330 position:73%
There are search tips specific to each catalog
and search system available through the Library

00:03:30.330 --> 00:03:33.900
of Congress, but today I'm going
to offer a few quick tips on how

00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:37.500
to achieve better results
when looking for images.

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:40.660 position:63%
The first primary tip is think visually.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:44.400
Use words to describe what
you hope to see in an image.

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:48.400 position:56%
For example, instead of trying World
War II home front as your search,

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:52.790
try victory garden, women
factory, scrap aluminum.

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:54.820
Use fewer words.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:59.120 position:69%
Many records in our catalogs are
transcriptions of a caption or caption card.

00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:05.250 position:69%
So, for instance, an individual's first name
may not be included or fully spelled out.

00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:08.880
Be sure to check the spelling
and spacing of your search words.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:10.770
Are there alternate spellings?

00:04:10.770 --> 00:04:15.530 position:61%
Could two words have been combined into
one or vice versa in image caption?

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:19.390 position:64%
For example, street car versus streetcar.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:22.050
Have you used abbreviations
that can be spelled out?

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:25.580
This is especially important
when searching for addresses.

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:29.990 position:64%
Avenue versus at A-V-E or street for S-T.

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:35.950 position:67%
Read descriptions of individual collections
to zero in on those relevant collections,

00:04:35.950 --> 00:04:40.120 position:61%
and browse the items within collections
to see how images are described

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:46.600 position:58%
and for ideas of search terms to try.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:49.310
While all types of visuals
can be useful in teaching,

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:52.500
today I'm going to talk primarily
about photographs.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:56.520 position:58%
Recently, I worked with architectural
and landscape historian Sam Waters

00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:01.510
to create a five-part video series
entitled "Every Photo is a Story".

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:06.580 position:69%
In this series, one of our goals was to both
share the stories captured in photos as well

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:10.560
as offer tips and tools for viewers
to use when studying photographs

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:13.520 position:63%
and learning directly from those images.

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:19.490 position:67%
The collection featured in the video series
contains 1,100 largely hand colored lantern

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:24.780 position:61%
slides of gardens created by
photographer Francis Benjamin Johnston.

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:29.200
The photos were created between
the 1910's and the 1930's.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:35.010 position:75%
To accompany the videos, I also created try it
yourself exercises which allow you to apply some

00:05:35.010 --> 00:05:39.310 position:56%
of the tips suggested in the videos
to other photographs and collections

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:41.410 position:61%
in the Prints and Photographs Division.

00:05:41.410 --> 00:05:46.490 position:63%
I hope you'll explore the videos and the
exercises for more hands-on practice.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:51.530 position:73%
Today I will walk us through the five sections
of the video and how they can offer a structure

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:57.070 position:56%
to guide you in getting more from a
photo than just a good illustration.

00:05:57.070 --> 00:06:01.330 position:58%
Part One, start to read a photograph,
suggests questions to the viewer

00:06:01.330 --> 00:06:05.940 position:59%
and potential researcher, starting
from perhaps the most patently obvious

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:08.030
and then digging a little deeper.

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:12.480 position:56%
The top tip suggests looking closely
at the image, front and back.

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:16.200
We suggests you ask questions and
make no assumptions about an image

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:19.660 position:59%
or its description, title, or caption.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:25.200 position:72%
Describe what you see, look for related photos
to put the image in context, and, finally,

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:28.090 position:72%
ask how the photographer is shaping the scene.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:30.700 position:73%
In this part, we introduced viewers to the idea

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:35.090 position:56%
that photographs are not necessarily
a mechanical recording of fact

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:37.510 position:63%
and should be studied with that in mind.

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:43.060 position:63%
In the time provided, we'll only be able
to touch on a few of the tips suggested

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:46.360
in each part, but I hope to give
a hint at what can be learned

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:49.370 position:64%
about a photograph with some exploration.

00:06:49.370 --> 00:06:54.880 position:72%
Let's start with a brief exercise based on the
tips for Part One, start to read a photograph.

00:06:54.880 --> 00:07:00.250 position:69%
Feel free to click on the link below the
image to view a larger version of the photo.

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:04.280 position:66%
I've selected a photograph from the Prints
and Photographs Division's collection.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:09.280 position:66%
This photo is also featured in one of the
Try it Yourself exercises available on the

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:11.890
"Every Photo is a Story" website.

00:07:11.890 --> 00:07:14.900
Take a moment to look closely
at this photograph.

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:19.570
Do you see details that might offer
clues to what is going on here?

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:22.350
What stands out to you as unusual?

00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:25.520 position:75%
What observations can you make about the people?

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:28.510
I'll let you look for a moment
before we continue.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:55.250
[ Pause ]

00:07:55.250 --> 00:08:00.620 position:63%
OK. I'm going to now give some examples
of what can be gathered by close looking

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:04.870
at the high resolution file
of these, of this image.

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:09.160
I always look for anything
with text on it in an image.

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:13.060 position:72%
A street sign, an address, name of a business,

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:18.470 position:64%
etc. Finding text within a photograph is
a great way to find out concrete details.

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:21.640
Let's look together at some of
the details I was able to observe

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.040
by zooming in on the digital image.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:28.360
Here we have the text of an oath
of allegiance to the United States.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:32.770 position:56%
It is also a renouncement of loyalty
to a previous foreign country.

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:40.200 position:73%
Looking closely at the people in the
classroom, at least two observations stand out.

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:44.670 position:67%
All of the people here have the appearance
of being students by virtue of being seated

00:08:44.670 --> 00:08:50.700 position:72%
at desks with books in front of them, but many
look older than the average college student.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:52.720 position:66%
Also, the people seated would appear to be

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:56.210
of different ethnicities based
on facial characteristics.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:09:00.520 position:59%
Combined with the oath, this starts to
suggest a reason they are in the room.

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:05.130
Let's keep looking.

00:09:05.130 --> 00:09:07.850 position:73%
More text can be found on the other chalkboard.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:12.820 position:64%
This one has the English alphabet as
well as an assignment to write sentences.

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.120
Taken on its own, this would
seem more appropriate

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.250 position:63%
to students in a grade school classroom.

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:20.430
So is this, in fact, a classroom?

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:23.720 position:59%
The two women standing in the
classroom, including this one in front

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:25.820 position:58%
of the assignment, could be teachers.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:29.870
They don't appear to have
recently vacated a student desk.

00:09:29.870 --> 00:09:34.870 position:70%
A really close look at the book in one of the
men's hands reveals an image of the Statue

00:09:34.870 --> 00:09:41.290 position:67%
of Liberty, a very strong symbol of America
and one often associated with immigrants.

00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:44.450
At this point, I try to speculate
what the photo is showing.

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:46.150
Who are these people?

00:09:46.150 --> 00:09:47.910
Why are they in a classroom?

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:51.390
Asking questions is the best
way to elicit answers.

00:09:51.390 --> 00:09:56.130 position:72%
It's also a good way to check your assumptions
and see if you have evidence to back them.

00:09:56.130 --> 00:09:59.540
I can assume this a classroom at
first glance, but it's important

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:03.100 position:75%
to then find reasons to support that assumption.

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:05.860 position:75%
With your observations and speculations in hand,

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:10.160
let's turn to the accompanying
information in the online catalog.

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:17.980 position:75%
The catalog records, which accompany images from
the Prints and Photographs Division vary widely

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:21.550
in the amount of detail and
type of information provided.

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:25.270 position:59%
This is often a function of what level
of cataloging was completed as well

00:10:25.270 --> 00:10:27.280 position:69%
as what the source for the descriptions was.

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.400 position:56%
A caption card file, the information
found on the object itself,

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:35.860 position:75%
a title divides by a visual materials cataloger.

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:39.620 position:59%
Different items in collections come
with different amounts of information.

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:42.010 position:66%
So you have to work with what is provided.

00:10:42.010 --> 00:10:50.060 position:59%
In this case, we are provided a very
simple title of Americanization class.

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:55.410 position:72%
If you go to the notes area of the catalog
description, you will see that the title comes

00:10:55.410 --> 00:11:00.100
from quote unverified data provided
by the National Photo Company

00:11:00.100 --> 00:11:02.300
on the negative or negative sleeve.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:04.510
This tells you a few things.

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:09.380 position:63%
The information, including the title,
have not been checked by a staff person,

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:13.650 position:59%
and that the words used came directly
from the time the photograph was taken

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:16.320
and from the source of the photo.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:19.620 position:70%
What does the word Americanization mean here?

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:23.180 position:64%
This is when it's helpful to compare your
observations and conclusions gathered

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:27.940 position:63%
by looking closely with what is
provided in written form with the photo.

00:11:27.940 --> 00:11:29.760
How well did they match up?

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.590
What were the differences?

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:35.070 position:61%
When you know the data is
unverified, it can pay to be skeptical,

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:38.000
and see if you can find visual
evidence to support

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.080 position:64%
or dispute the provided title or caption.

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:48.760 position:61%
Another tip we offer in Part One of the
webcast is to search for related photos

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:53.140
in the same collection as well as
outside that specific collection.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:57.810 position:59%
I can start the search by typing the
title I was given into a search blank.

00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:02.290 position:64%
A search for Americanization class in the
same collection offers a close variant

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:04.340
to the photo we started with.

00:12:04.340 --> 00:12:10.040 position:70%
Studying this image offers additional
insight and likely stimulates more questions.

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:12.150 position:61%
Explore other photos in the collection.

00:12:12.150 --> 00:12:13.780
What kind of photos are they?

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.380
What kinds of topics do they cover?

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:20.890 position:75%
Searching elsewhere in the collection could also
offer different perspectives on the photograph,

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:24.070
and place it within a new context.

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:28.200
I'm going to turn it over
to Tom for a few slides now.

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:32.770 position:56%
&gt;&gt; As you're preparing to use images
with students, you'll want to think

00:12:32.770 --> 00:12:35.730 position:73%
about how students will access the image files.

00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:39.680 position:67%
They may be looking at the image on a
projector screen or interactive whiteboard.

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:43.220
They may be looking at the image on
their own device or on a desktop,

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:46.580
laptop, or tablet in a small group.

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:49.450 position:73%
They may be looking at a printout of the image.

00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:52.560 position:59%
A lot of this will have to do with
the technology that's available to you

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:55.910
and your students, and some of
this may be based on the level

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:58.860 position:64%
and detail you want your students to see.

00:12:58.860 --> 00:13:02.110 position:66%
Printing the image will not allow, usually
allow you to see some of the details

00:13:02.110 --> 00:13:06.040 position:66%
that Christy just pointed out in the photo
we were looking at, and in that case,

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:07.490 position:61%
you'll want to view the file digitally,

00:13:07.490 --> 00:13:11.290 position:61%
and you'll want to download the
highest resolution tif file if you can.

00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:16.210 position:75%
Just like any large file, if you have the
opportunity, download these files ahead of time.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:19.250
It can save you from any Internet
hiccups or long download times

00:13:19.250 --> 00:13:20.900 position:61%
that you can experience in your school.

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.390 position:66%
If the image doesn't contain fine details,

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:28.560
the largest jpeg file could be
acceptable for viewing on a screen.

00:13:28.560 --> 00:13:32.780 position:75%
When printing, I usually do a test print to make
sure that I'm able to see the level of detail

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:38.340
and sharpness that will allow my
students to analyze the image.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:42.400
Speaking of analyzing, the Library
of Congress has a teachers' page

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:48.550 position:64%
at loc dot gov slash teachers that has a
primary source analysis tool for students

00:13:48.550 --> 00:13:51.980
and teacher question prompts
to help with image analysis.

00:13:51.980 --> 00:13:54.460
Here, I'm on the Library
of Congress teachers' page.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:59.440 position:75%
On the left, I clicked on using primary sources,

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:03.660
then I clicked on teachers'
guide and analysis tool.

00:14:03.660 --> 00:14:07.290 position:56%
The primary source analysis tool can
be filled out and printed online,

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:09.460
or there's a link to a pdf version.

00:14:09.460 --> 00:14:13.160
I'll show that you in a, an
example of that in just a moment.

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:14.580
The teachers' guide is a pdf.

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:19.240
Here's the teachers' guide.

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:24.910 position:64%
You'll notice that it's organized in four
categories - observe, reflect, question,

00:14:24.910 --> 00:14:28.460 position:64%
and at the bottom, further investigation.

00:14:28.460 --> 00:14:32.560 position:64%
These are the steps that we want students
to go through when analyzing an image.

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:36.950 position:58%
Observations are going to be specific
things that can be seen in the photo.

00:14:36.950 --> 00:14:41.960 position:61%
So you may ask what did you notice
first, or what is the physical setting?

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:45.780 position:61%
Making observations are what we've done
in the first step of Christy's analysis

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:48.770 position:64%
of this photo, of the photo from earlier.

00:14:48.770 --> 00:14:52.410
Reflections ask students to infer
based on their observations as well

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:54.260 position:63%
as their own understanding of the world.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:57.690 position:70%
So I might ask what's happening in the image.

00:14:57.690 --> 00:15:02.470 position:69%
They will bring in their observations of the
photo and what they know about classrooms

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:07.440 position:58%
to make it reflections in their
analysis, and questions are just that

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:11.430 position:63%
but can sometimes be difficult, a
difficult part of analysis for students.

00:15:11.430 --> 00:15:13.730 position:67%
What does this photo make you wonder about?

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:15.600
What is still a mystery to you?

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:17.770 position:56%
What do you want to know more about?

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:23.100 position:63%
Those questions that students ask can
help guide next steps in their thinking.

00:15:23.100 --> 00:15:26.510 position:56%
At the bottom are suggestions for
how students can show their learning

00:15:26.510 --> 00:15:28.980
from their photo analysis.

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:35.590 position:56%
This is mockup of the primary source
analysis tool that students may use.

00:15:35.590 --> 00:15:39.110
You'll notice it has the same
categories as the teachers' guide.

00:15:39.110 --> 00:15:42.860 position:64%
I want to point out a few things that I
encourage when my students are analyzing.

00:15:42.860 --> 00:15:46.540
First, I don't ask them to
write in complete sentences.

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:47.940
Some do naturally.

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:51.510 position:56%
Others like to list things,
especially when making observations.

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:55.990
Second, you might notice the arrows
drawn between the categories.

00:15:55.990 --> 00:15:59.970 position:59%
I sometimes ask my students to do this
to help them explain their thinking.

00:15:59.970 --> 00:16:04.290
Students' reflections and questions
should naturally connect to one

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:06.160 position:58%
or more things they saw in the image.

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:11.550 position:73%
So, for example, if a student in the reflection
writes that they think this is a classroom,

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:16.180 position:58%
but in their observations has nothing
written that relates to a classroom,

00:16:16.180 --> 00:16:18.540 position:75%
they haven't really made their thinking visible.

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:20.990
That, of course, doesn't mean that
they aren't thinking about it,

00:16:20.990 --> 00:16:26.170 position:70%
but making those thoughts visible through the
primary source analysis tool can help them

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:32.030 position:75%
when they're sharing their ideas or taking that
analysis into a larger aspect of their learning.

00:16:32.030 --> 00:16:34.970 position:75%
Also, and you can't see it through this example,

00:16:34.970 --> 00:16:41.520 position:59%
but a student analyzing an image using
this tool is not a linear process.

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:43.970
They don't fill out all of
their observations and then all

00:16:43.970 --> 00:16:46.650
of their reflections and
then all of their questions.

00:16:46.650 --> 00:16:48.630
I'm expecting them to jump around.

00:16:48.630 --> 00:16:51.000 position:72%
Many of them start with an observation or two.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.170 position:73%
It's a natural starting point, but then they'll
move between the three columns from there.

00:16:55.170 --> 00:17:01.450 position:73%
And, finally, my recommendation, if you have
students who have never read an image before is

00:17:01.450 --> 00:17:04.790
to model this with them as a whole
group, much like Christy did,

00:17:04.790 --> 00:17:07.490 position:59%
started to do with the previous image.

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:11.840 position:58%
No matter how old they are, have them
do another in pairs or small groups.

00:17:11.840 --> 00:17:17.140 position:72%
You'll be surprised how that collaboration can
help students see things or think about things

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:19.520
that they would not on their own.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:23.110
With that base knowledge of the
tools, students and teachers have

00:17:23.110 --> 00:17:29.720 position:63%
at their disposal let's dive deeper into
the analysis of our image with Christy.

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:30.880
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Tom.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:36.700 position:69%
Those were all great points, and those tools
must come in extremely handy in a classroom.

00:17:36.700 --> 00:17:39.260
Let's move on to Part Two.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:43.820 position:66%
In Part Two, get to know the photographer,
we look to the person behind the camera

00:17:43.820 --> 00:17:50.030 position:73%
and ask viewers to apply basic research skills,
much as one might with any research topic.

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:55.300 position:67%
The researcher should consult secondary
reference sources, both printed and online,

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:59.490
track down primary sources such
as magazine and newspaper articles

00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:04.740 position:73%
from the photographer's lifetime, and if you're
lucky, locate the papers and the photographer.

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:10.750 position:75%
Use these sources to establish a chronology of
key dates and places in the photographer's life.

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:17.240 position:59%
As with title and caption
information, the information available

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:21.880 position:58%
about the photographer can vary
widely, and understanding that is key

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:23.980 position:58%
to working with archival collections.

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:27.700
In some cases, we not only know the
photographer but know a great deal

00:18:27.700 --> 00:18:31.890
about the photographer's
life, influences, and career.

00:18:31.890 --> 00:18:35.830 position:66%
In other cases, we know the
photographer's name but little about them.

00:18:35.830 --> 00:18:40.190 position:64%
And as in this case, we sometimes do not
know the name of the photographer at all.

00:18:40.190 --> 00:18:44.810
As you can see, there's no creator
listed in our catalog record.

00:18:44.810 --> 00:18:49.250 position:73%
When we do not know the photographer, and even
when we do, it's good to turn to the collection

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:52.190 position:64%
which the photo is part of to learn more.

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:55.200
That information is provided
in the record itself as well

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:58.670 position:61%
as at the top right in the part of box.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:02.290
Clicking the link there takes you
to the home page of the collection.

00:19:02.290 --> 00:19:09.880 position:75%
On this home page for the collection, there will
away be an about this collection entry as well

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:14.440
as sometimes articles and
essays about the collection.

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:19.580 position:64%
In many cases, these include biographical
information, the scope of the collection,

00:19:19.580 --> 00:19:25.550 position:72%
explanations of how the collection was
acquired, cataloged, digitized, and organized.

00:19:25.550 --> 00:19:30.390 position:64%
Learning this information places the
single photograph into a telling context.

00:19:30.390 --> 00:19:36.090 position:59%
In Part Three, consider how the photos
were made, we shift our attention

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:38.630 position:56%
from the photographer to the object.

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:43.180 position:56%
In the case of the video series, the
photo and the colored lantern slide.

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:45.610
Consider the original photograph.

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:46.720
What size is it?

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:47.740
What format?

00:19:47.740 --> 00:19:50.170
What camera was used to create it?

00:19:50.170 --> 00:19:53.660
How does this influence your
understanding of the image?

00:19:53.660 --> 00:19:57.610
Take into consider what happens
after the shutter snaps.

00:19:57.610 --> 00:20:00.820
What changes or manipulations
may have been made?

00:20:00.820 --> 00:20:04.090
Consider the photographer's time
involved in making the image.

00:20:04.090 --> 00:20:10.010 position:72%
Consider the client, the purpose of the
photo, the audience for which it was intended.

00:20:10.010 --> 00:20:13.150
Today we're going to focus on
how thinking about the audience

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:17.930
for a photograph affects how
we view and understand it.

00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:22.160 position:59%
Let's return to the information about
the National Photo Company collection.

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:26.800 position:59%
This photo of an Americanization class
was taken by a photographer working

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:31.240 position:61%
for the National Photo Company, but who
was the target audience for the photo?

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:33.350
Why was this photo taken?

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:38.190 position:67%
There are a few places this information can
be gleaned for the collection as a whole.

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:43.780 position:70%
One is the about this collection and the
supporting documents I mentioned in Part Two.

00:20:43.780 --> 00:20:46.420 position:70%
The other is what is known as a guide record.

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:50.040 position:61%
These can be found in the Library of
Congress online catalog for collections

00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:52.810 position:64%
from the Prints and Photographs Division.

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:56.180
They are compact summaries
of creator, date, subject,

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:59.570
and historical information
for an entire collection.

00:20:59.570 --> 00:21:03.920 position:59%
You can see part of what such a record
looks like at the right of the slide.

00:21:05.210 --> 00:21:10.580 position:75%
By reading over the about this collection and
the guide record for the National Photo Company,

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:14.680
I find information about different
audiences for the photographs.

00:21:14.680 --> 00:21:20.960 position:73%
According to these two documents, photographers
for the NPCC undertook photographic assignments

00:21:20.960 --> 00:21:26.740 position:75%
for local businesses and government agencies,
and they also took photos to sell to newspapers,

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:30.870 position:69%
news distributors, and other photo agencies.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:35.920 position:64%
We don't know at this time why this
photograph was taken or for what purpose.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:40.350 position:58%
How do you think the audience for the
photo would affect how it was framed?

00:21:40.350 --> 00:21:43.090
What would be included or left out?

00:21:43.090 --> 00:21:48.780 position:59%
The photographer has control over when
and how he or she takes the photo.

00:21:48.780 --> 00:21:53.910 position:72%
For example, a photographer working for a
news agency might be thinking about the market

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:56.650 position:70%
for this photo while the photographer working

00:21:56.650 --> 00:22:00.110
for a government agency sponsoring
this class might want

00:22:00.110 --> 00:22:03.340 position:70%
to show the class in the best possible light.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:07.340
Can you guess the audience just
by looking at the photograph?

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:10.510 position:63%
What evidence supports your speculation?

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:15.890
[ Background Sounds ]

00:22:15.890 --> 00:22:21.180 position:70%
Part Four takes a broader view by
suggesting we explore the photographer's era.

00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:26.450
Like any art form, photographs
are not created in a vacuum.

00:22:26.450 --> 00:22:29.290
We discuss the time period
during which the work was made.

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:33.110 position:59%
In the case of the videos, Johnston's
work was taking place during the heart

00:22:33.110 --> 00:22:36.120
of the progressive era and
the city beautiful movement,

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:40.390
and that certainly influenced her
choices and the work she received.

00:22:40.390 --> 00:22:46.490 position:73%
Aesthetic preferences, art movements, landscape
design, composition, all of these had an impact

00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:51.490
on the work Johnston did as
well as how it was received.

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:56.950 position:73%
One way to learn about the photographer's era
is to turn to published sources like newspapers

00:22:56.950 --> 00:22:59.320
and magazines of the time period.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:03.660 position:61%
"Chronically in America" on the Library
of Congress website offers free access

00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:07.810
to digitized newspapers dating
from 1836 to 1922.

00:23:07.810 --> 00:23:12.680 position:61%
To try and answer my own question about
audience for the photograph as well

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:18.090 position:70%
as what the term Americanization meant at the
time of the photo, I tried a simple search

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:21.230
for the phrase Americanization
class and was lucky enough

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:24.410 position:75%
to get the page on the right as my first result.

00:23:24.410 --> 00:23:28.230 position:56%
At lower right, I find the exact
photograph we've been talking about.

00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:30.130
Let's look a little closer.

00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:37.480 position:66%
As you can see at lower right, this search
gave me several new pieces of information.

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:41.450
A more complete caption,
where the photo was taken,

00:23:41.450 --> 00:23:44.320 position:66%
what nationalities the students represent,

00:23:44.320 --> 00:23:49.050 position:56%
confirmation that the women standing
are the teachers, and their names.

00:23:49.050 --> 00:23:54.020 position:75%
We also now have more information about the
date as this photo was featured in the August 8,

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:57.860
1920, edition of the "Sunday Star".

00:23:57.860 --> 00:24:02.440 position:73%
I also know that at least one audience for this
photograph was this newspaper in Washington,

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:08.780 position:73%
D.C. By reading the rest of the page to see
what other photos were featured in this section

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:12.860 position:66%
as well as pursuing the other results from
my search in "Chronically in America",

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:18.660 position:75%
I can also start to glean more information about
this photo and the time period it belongs to.

00:24:18.660 --> 00:24:23.380
I can find more hints about the
term Americanization as well.

00:24:25.730 --> 00:24:28.880
The fifth and final part is where
we pull the threads together

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:30.880 position:61%
to interpret the stories we discovered.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:35.750 position:56%
In the top tips for this section, we
reinforce the themes of each part.

00:24:35.750 --> 00:24:41.180 position:69%
We encouraged viewers to look closely at the
photographs to study who took the picture,

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:47.760 position:72%
to search for related written information, and
to ask lots of questions and to ask for help.

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:52.110 position:58%
As always, we encourage you to seek
out reference librarians like myself,

00:24:52.110 --> 00:24:55.270 position:66%
archivists, historians, and other experts.

00:24:55.270 --> 00:25:02.440
So keeping all that in mind, what
is the story of this photograph?

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:05.790
We know a bit more about the
circumstances of the photo now.

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:10.570
We have the who, what, when,
where, and how of the image.

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:15.070 position:70%
This is a good point to think about the photo
itself, and then to step outside the photo

00:25:15.070 --> 00:25:20.860 position:56%
and ask how this photo fits into
the bigger story of America in 1920.

00:25:20.860 --> 00:25:24.470
And I'm going to turn things over
to Tom, and he'll tell you how

00:25:24.470 --> 00:25:27.350 position:67%
to bring these strategies to the classroom.

00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:28.250
&gt;&gt; Thanks, Christy.

00:25:28.250 --> 00:25:32.680
The final step that Christy asked
us to do here, and if I can,

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:35.530 position:63%
I'm going to go back to these questions.

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:40.070 position:66%
They are really the further investigations
that we would ask students to do.

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:42.040 position:56%
What's the story of this photograph?

00:25:42.040 --> 00:25:47.410
How does this story fit into the
story of America in the 1920's?

00:25:47.410 --> 00:25:50.440
How does a student then share
what he or she knows?

00:25:50.440 --> 00:25:56.240 position:69%
How do they fit it into the larger context
of a time period or an event or a biography?

00:25:56.240 --> 00:26:01.740 position:63%
This is truly where analysis and images
fits into student thinking and learning.

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:07.750 position:61%
A final few things to think about when
including images into student learning.

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:10.770 position:70%
How do you want students to access the image?

00:26:10.770 --> 00:26:13.970 position:72%
Are they given to the students by the teacher?

00:26:13.970 --> 00:26:18.790 position:70%
Are the students going to be searching for
images on their own, and what kind of time is

00:26:18.790 --> 00:26:22.810 position:67%
that going to take and skill on their part?

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:25.040 position:56%
Regarding bibliographic information.

00:26:25.040 --> 00:26:28.210 position:69%
Do you want students to have it all at once?

00:26:28.210 --> 00:26:29.390
When should they have it?

00:26:29.390 --> 00:26:34.730 position:63%
Sometimes like in our example today, you
want them just thinking about the photo

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:40.540 position:70%
and asking questions before they have any of
the bibliographic information that gives some

00:26:40.540 --> 00:26:44.810
of those answers, but may lead
to other questions and searches

00:26:44.810 --> 00:26:47.770
like we saw with our image today.

00:26:47.770 --> 00:26:50.190 position:61%
Don't forget about the creator's voice.

00:26:50.190 --> 00:26:54.560 position:58%
It's very easy to focus so much on
what the camera caught that we forget

00:26:54.560 --> 00:26:59.910 position:73%
that the person behind it was taking that photo
for a reason, and that reason reveals some

00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:03.860 position:72%
of the story that he or she is trying to tell.

00:27:03.860 --> 00:27:09.380 position:70%
Be thinking before your students even ask for
it about other sources that can be brought

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:13.800 position:59%
in to complement the image, both
primary sources and secondary sources,

00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:16.250 position:63%
and this happens for one of two reasons.

00:27:16.250 --> 00:27:20.860 position:61%
Either the other resource is
informing the students about the photo,

00:27:20.860 --> 00:27:24.430
or the photo is informing the
students about the other resource.

00:27:24.430 --> 00:27:30.870 position:69%
So thinking about how all of those resources
fit together and playing with those ideas

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:36.570 position:56%
as a teacher can really lead to deep
layered learning on students' parts.

00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:41.380 position:61%
And, finally, from personal experience,
this may look messy the first time.

00:27:41.380 --> 00:27:45.980
Students may not get to where you
want them to be in their thinking.

00:27:45.980 --> 00:27:50.880 position:69%
While extremely beneficial, it's not always
intuitive for students to learn in this way,

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:53.350
and it wasn't intuitive for
me to teach in this way.

00:27:53.350 --> 00:28:00.800 position:59%
I had to try it, reflect on the steps,
