of the image is really beneficial.

00:31:03.410 --> 00:31:05.040
They are tactile.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:06.010
They want to touch it.

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:10.420 position:59%
They want to point to it, and they
want to kind of get their hands on it.

00:31:10.420 --> 00:31:16.990 position:70%
If they can have a pencil or a crayon and
circle, mark on the image, that is wonderful.

00:31:16.990 --> 00:31:20.430 position:64%
Now if you work with the little ones, you
know they're going to be talking anyway.

00:31:20.430 --> 00:31:23.400
So you might as well make it
as collaborative as possible.

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:25.670
Give them a couple of minutes
to talk to a partner.

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:28.520
Then bring it back and talk
with the whole group.

00:31:28.520 --> 00:31:33.950 position:75%
You're going to really start to tease out ideas
and get this wonderful collective thinking going

00:31:33.950 --> 00:31:39.050
on when you have all of that, all
of those ideas thrown out together.

00:31:39.050 --> 00:31:47.820 position:70%
And have an idea of what you think, where you
think, excuse me, students are going to go,

00:31:47.820 --> 00:31:51.020 position:58%
but also be open for different ideas.

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:56.770 position:63%
I know that when we work with older
students or when we do this with adults,

00:31:56.770 --> 00:32:00.480 position:66%
we have a really strong idea of where
they're going to go because we are adults.

00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:06.150 position:72%
So we're closer in age, but I've always find
myself surprised what students find important,

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:10.600 position:64%
and on that note, sometimes I also really
target those observations with questions

00:32:10.600 --> 00:32:14.710 position:67%
like what do you think is important in this
image, or what do you think is interesting

00:32:14.710 --> 00:32:18.680 position:63%
in this image, and I might need to ask
them follow-up questions to really start

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:22.980 position:66%
to understand their thinking because they
may not be able to initially verbalize it.

00:32:22.980 --> 00:32:29.660 position:56%
So those are a few ideas for working
with images with younger students.

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:34.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Tom, a follow-up question to that
is what has surprised you in working

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:37.810
with students on, using pictures.

00:32:39.100 --> 00:32:44.460 position:70%
&gt;&gt; I'd say simply that I try to think through
every direction that they are going to go

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:50.010 position:67%
with their observations, their reflections,
and their questions, and, inevitably,

00:32:50.010 --> 00:32:56.940 position:61%
even when I've done a, an analysis with
a group of five, six, seven year olds,

00:32:56.940 --> 00:33:03.180 position:70%
and since I'm in the Library, I'll do it with
three classes, I can come back the next year,

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:08.560 position:75%
and I can have a student bring back up something
that not only did I not think of but those 60,

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:11.510 position:69%
70, 80 kids the year before didn't think of.

00:33:11.510 --> 00:33:15.790 position:63%
And so it's just being open to all those
directions, and I find myself having

00:33:15.790 --> 00:33:22.160 position:66%
to really step back and make sure that I'm
not guiding that image analysis too much.

00:33:22.160 --> 00:33:27.110 position:64%
That I'm listening to what they're saying
and then asking them clarifying questions

00:33:27.110 --> 00:33:31.860
to let them lead the analysis so
I don't shut down that thinking.

00:33:31.860 --> 00:33:36.930 position:59%
&gt;&gt; Could you talk a little bit about
the kinds of the items that excite you

00:33:36.930 --> 00:33:45.490 position:66%
as teacher/librarian or that your students
have responded particularly well to?

00:33:45.490 --> 00:33:50.120
&gt;&gt; I think the key thing that
I like to do is two things.

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:54.570
First of all, bring in images
that have other children in them.

00:33:54.570 --> 00:33:57.390 position:73%
My students seem to react really well to those.

00:33:57.390 --> 00:34:01.590
They feel like they're in a place
where they can speak to that.

00:34:01.590 --> 00:34:04.830
It could be images at school,
at home, on the street.

00:34:04.830 --> 00:34:06.930
It doesn't seem to matter.

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:09.590
They react to images of children.

00:34:09.590 --> 00:34:12.830 position:59%
And then the other thing, and this has
to do with when you bring the image

00:34:12.830 --> 00:34:21.480 position:59%
in to do the analysis, bringing it in
before, I've had less success bringing

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:26.880 position:59%
that in before students are, have any
exposure with their classroom teacher.

00:34:26.880 --> 00:34:30.400 position:66%
More often, once they have a little bit of
background with their classroom teacher,

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:36.510 position:72%
maybe not too much, but that's a great time to
bring in a photo to start to look at that idea

00:34:36.510 --> 00:34:40.240 position:70%
in a different way or in a deeper way because
they'll have a little bit of a grounding,

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:44.870 position:59%
and they'll feel like they can really
contribute something to that analysis.

00:34:44.870 --> 00:34:52.440
&gt;&gt; So, Tom, go ahead, and there's
another follow-up question for you.

00:34:52.440 --> 00:34:55.510
Do you ever use props related
to what's in the photograph

00:34:55.510 --> 00:34:58.630 position:66%
to make the experience more multi-sensory?

00:34:58.630 --> 00:35:04.760
&gt;&gt; I'm trying to think of an
example where I have done that,

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:08.070 position:75%
and to be completely honest with you, I haven't.

00:35:08.070 --> 00:35:15.710 position:66%
I think probably the closest we've done is
we've had some images of school settings

00:35:15.710 --> 00:35:19.740 position:64%
that we've analyzed, and we have walked
around the school to clarify some things.

00:35:19.740 --> 00:35:23.880
Sometimes a group will, and this
is where things get interesting

00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:26.300
when students have disagreements.

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:29.220
So how do you resolve that
dis, those disagreements,

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:33.360 position:59%
and the place where you can resolve
disagreements are in the observations.

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:36.380 position:75%
You should be able to agree on the observations.

00:35:36.380 --> 00:35:41.470 position:59%
You may not agree on the reflections,
but you can agree on the observations.

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:45.810
So when students are trying
to bring in their own context,

00:35:45.810 --> 00:35:48.590 position:69%
and we can get quick access to that context.

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:52.990 position:66%
So we can get quick access to those school
settings, then take advantage of that,

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:58.780
and so I think in that sense, those
props, those, that may be related

00:35:58.780 --> 00:36:04.090
to the photograph would be a great
way to [inaudible] that context

00:36:04.090 --> 00:36:07.060 position:70%
and give them another way that they can bring

00:36:07.060 --> 00:36:11.340
in their own knowledge to
then reflect on the photo.

00:36:11.340 --> 00:36:17.110 position:64%
&gt;&gt; One point I was going to make is that
the same photo can offer different levels

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:19.850 position:61%
of information for different audiences.

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:25.400 position:73%
So even though our "Every Photo is a Story"
series is kind of geared towards older students

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:28.770 position:73%
or adults, it's possible to take the same photo

00:36:28.770 --> 00:36:31.940
and change the kind of questions
you're asking to.

00:36:31.940 --> 00:36:36.340 position:56%
If you take, for an example, we have
photographs of Civil War soldiers.

00:36:36.340 --> 00:36:41.740 position:66%
So if you show some, a young student a
photograph of an African American soldier,

00:36:41.740 --> 00:36:46.180
it will definitely give them
questions about what was the role

00:36:46.180 --> 00:36:48.400 position:59%
of African Americans in the Civil War.

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:50.570
They may or may not know that.

00:36:50.570 --> 00:36:54.790
They can look at the person
and observe how old they are.

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:56.540 position:73%
You know, does that person look older than you?

00:36:56.540 --> 00:37:01.010
Things like that, and then
you can take that same photo

00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:03.870
to a different level with
different interest groups.

00:37:03.870 --> 00:37:05.600 position:64%
So some people are studying the uniforms.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:09.180
Some people are determining
what states they fought for.

00:37:09.180 --> 00:37:11.720 position:66%
What state, what kind of soldier they are.

00:37:11.720 --> 00:37:15.680 position:59%
So it's just a point to make that,
just because you see a photograph used

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:19.610 position:59%
for a certain age group, it's possible
that you can look at it a different,

00:37:19.610 --> 00:37:24.320
from a different angle and offer
it to a younger audience as well.

