00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:29.960 position:73%
A little insight into your life as a
reference librarian, and what gets you excited?

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:32.060
&gt;&gt; I, you know, one of the
things that's exciting for me is

00:38:32.060 --> 00:38:34.990
that I get a different kind
of question every day.

00:38:34.990 --> 00:38:37.060 position:59%
There's certainly recurring questions.

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:43.630 position:75%
We have people, since we're in DC, people often
come in and ask for help finding historic photos

00:38:43.630 --> 00:38:48.780 position:59%
of the place they live, or an area
they know in DC, and that's always fun

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:54.330 position:75%
because it is definitely a treasure hunt through
our collections to find that exact location

00:38:54.330 --> 00:38:56.840 position:64%
at the time period they're interested in.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:02.720 position:73%
But something I find interesting as when a user
comes to me and wants to use visual materials

00:39:02.720 --> 00:39:04.310 position:56%
in a way I hadn't thought of before.

00:39:04.310 --> 00:39:12.380 position:69%
I had a researcher come in who was actually
looking at some of our 18th century drawings

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:15.570
for a modern purpose, and,
typically, folks who are looking

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:19.180
at those older drawings,
it's are an academic reason.

00:39:19.180 --> 00:39:23.850 position:66%
And this gentleman was actually part of
an archeological dig, and they were trying

00:39:23.850 --> 00:39:30.620 position:58%
to find artifacts from the French and
Indian War, if I remember correctly,

00:39:30.620 --> 00:39:37.320 position:72%
and he was able to use drawings done in 1760
to actually pinpoint an area that he was going

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:43.100 position:66%
to go back and look into and try to find a
structure of a fort from that time period.

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:47.420 position:63%
So it was a use for that particular
drawing I had not occurred to me before.

00:39:47.420 --> 00:39:51.830 position:58%
And I try to, you know, a lot of the
questions that come to mind I feature

00:39:51.830 --> 00:39:57.240 position:69%
in our Picture This blog, which is a fun
way for me to explore them or share the kind

00:39:57.240 --> 00:39:59.700
of discoveries I make day by day.

00:39:59.700 --> 00:40:05.920 position:69%
I wanted to go back to quickly to an earlier
mention of students who love mysteries,

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:10.540 position:67%
and one thing I would point out that if you
go back to the Picture This blog as well

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:13.050
as the Flickr account for
the Library of Congress,

00:40:13.050 --> 00:40:19.570 position:69%
you'll see that recently we've actually been
posting what we call our mystery photos.

00:40:19.570 --> 00:40:25.050 position:69%
We have collections for which there are no
captions on the photos, and we are selecting

00:40:25.050 --> 00:40:29.810 position:66%
out groups of them, ones that we think are
solvable mysteries, and we're posting them

00:40:29.810 --> 00:40:34.010
on our Flickr account and asking
people to try to figure it out.

00:40:34.010 --> 00:40:37.660
So we don't actually know
the answer in many cases.

00:40:37.660 --> 00:40:42.720 position:66%
So it is a true challenge for people, and
we do get a really good response for that,

00:40:42.720 --> 00:40:47.110 position:59%
and I think it would be an interesting
lesson for perhaps older students,

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:49.740
some of them are tricky, but
there's certainly clues there

00:40:49.740 --> 00:40:52.360 position:58%
that would appeal to many age groups.

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:57.660 position:75%
So that's something that we try to do and
engage people with our photos in different ways.

